name: Tarik Brown
text: Hey everyone! The beta version of a start-up project that I’ve been working with has finally been released. STUDIA is meant to be an affordable and accessible alternative to using textbook problems to study. Every single problem is unique to us made by physics grad students at ND. For now we have decided to do a rushed and free beta release in light of COVID -19 to help students prepare for finals. Right now we only cover physics 1 topics but we are looking to expand to other science subjects in the future. Please share https://studia.app/ with any students you know taking a physics 1 course, even if you are not taking physics, take a moment to take a look and give feedback using the link in our homepage. We are currently in the semi-final round of McCloskey so all feedback helps!

text: So you want to set each of the conditions in enm {} to be a different bitmask so then you can use them to check if conditions are on or off using the binary you created when parsing the command line

name: Katelyn Wyatt
text: A bitmask (at least to my understanding) is a series of 1s and 0s that you use to overlay with other binary numbers to evaluate something. For instance, let's say you have 4 conditions you might want to check so you have 0000. If you want to activate two of those conditions, you might have the pattern 1001 or 0110, etc depending on which conditions you want activated. Let's say you have 1010, you want to first condition to activate and the third. Now the question is, how do you check which values are 1s and which ones are 0s. You use a bitmask. So the bitmask for the first condition would be 1000. When you & 1010 with 1000, it'll return 1000, a non-zero integer (when converted to integer form), which indicated the condition is on. If the condition was off, let's say you & 0010 with 1000, it'll return 0000, or just 0 as an int, and you therefore know the condition is turned off
